title: For Sale:  FEG P9M
postcontent: Selling an FEG P9M. Includes original box and one magazine. This is the later P9M model with the S&W style lockup, extended controls, and improved sights, but normal Hi-Power trigger and general operation. It's compatible with all Hi-Power parts except for the barrel, slide and frame. I've installed a full set of Wolff standard weight springs (Service Pak Type 1) and a Browning extractor and roll pin. Includes all the original springs, the extractor, and the extractor roll pin.THIS PISTOL IS IN NEED OF MINOR REPAIR. I'm selling because I believe it's having a problem with the sear. I was a sucker and bought this from the last owner without much inspection.When I got the P9M it was in rough shape, so I cleaned it up and replaced all the springs and the extractor. I've put ~300 rounds through it and it feeds and cycles fine, but in the last 150 rounds I got three "bursts" of two rounds. From reading up it sounds like the sear is either worn or the last owner messed with it.It's possible that the "bursts" were not the sear slipping but bump fires, as the trigger lever has been shortened to shorten the reset (at the cost of added takeup). Reset is currently very short, similar to a 1911. That's an $8 part to replace and takes 30 seconds to change. I just don't want to deal with it anymore so I'm selling the pistol cheap with full disclosure. With an $8 trigger lever and $30 sear and (maybe) some minor fitting, this pistol will be returned to factory spec and should work 100%. There are no other functional issues apart from what I describe.Asking $300 OBO. Would also consider a trade for other 9mm handguns. Can add a little cash for a more expensive trade.If you have any questions at all, or want more pictures, please call or text me at 248-679-6602.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stevens Model 200 20 gauge pump shotgun
postcontent:
Stevens Model 200 20 gauge pump shotgun. Here is a rare one for the shotgun collector. The Model 200 was manufactured from 1911 to 1914, with only 20,000 produced.  Serial no. 189XX.

The last patent date is 1912. I purchased this gun from a Stevens collector years ago.  Shot trap with it once, using Winchester Super Target 2 3/4" 7/8oz. #8 Shot, and the gun performed flawlessly.  Then cleaned the gun and stored it in my safe ever since.  Gun comes with a file of information including patent drawings, a component parts list, and a 1968 "Guns & Ammo" magazine with an article about the Model 200.  This gun also includes the spanner, which is a part often missing from Model 200s these days. 

The Stevens Model 200, 20 gauge pump shotgun was the first manufactured 20 Gauge Pump Shotgun. It was the brainchild of the famous trap shooter, Charles (Sparrow) Young. Sparrow Young is in the trapshooting hall of fame and was the first shooter to break 100 straight from back yardage. In 1910 he patented the original idea which became the Model 200.  The gun was meant to be a combination of a light "field" type gun for upland game with a heavy duck gun (when firing 3" shells).

 

The Stevens Model 200 was considered the King of The Turkey Shoot Circuit in the 1920's. This is a 5-shot gun that weighs about 6.5 lbs.  Note that the stock's drop was well-modified by a previous owner (see pics). Additional pics available upon request.

 

For FTF sale in VA, buyer must be 18+ years of age and have a VA driver’s license.  For an out-of-state sale, will arrange shipment to buyer’s FFL, at buyer’s cost.

Asking $600.  Open to reasonable offers / trades.

Transaction will include bill of sale. Still available if posted.  Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Meprolight Tru-Dot RDS
postcontent: I have a Meprolight Tru-Dot RDS for trade/sale. It uses AA batteries, has a built in QD mounting system, and has an auto-on that turns the sight on with the slightest movement of the firearm. The sight works very well. It has a simple interface. Just a twist knob on the side that selects the four different brightness settings. The lowest setting is compatible with night vision if you have it. The other three are low, medium, and high settings. I have yet to see the dot get washed out on high. It is a 1.8 MOA dot so if you adjust your brightness settings accordingly, you can be very accurate with it.The auto-on feature is awesome and works very well. In the two years I have had this sight, it has never been off by the time that I looked through the optic. The motion sensor is very sensitive so just tapping the table with the firearm resting on it will activate the sight.Battery life is around 20,000 hours on full brightness, but the motion sensor extends that lifetime. That is on a single lithium AA battery which you can find everywhere.If you want more information or pictures of specific things let me know.
